-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Determine the units digit of 16¹⁷ · 17¹⁸ · 18¹⁹. 2. [Key Idea] Work modulo 10: reduce each base to its last digit and exploit the short cyclic patterns of powers of 6, 7, 8 mod 10. 3. [Proof] Let the product be P = 16¹⁷ · 17¹⁸ · 18¹⁹. Because we only need the units digit, compute P mod 10: a) 16 ≡ 6 (mod 10). For any k ≥ 1, 6ᵏ ≡ 6 (mod 10). ⇒ 16¹⁷ ≡ 6 (mod 10). b) 17 ≡ 7 (mod 10). Powers of 7 mod 10 cycle every 4: 7¹≡7, 7²≡9, 7³≡3, 7⁴≡1. 18 ≡ 2 (mod 4) ⇒ 7¹⁸ ≡ 7² ≡ 9 (mod 10). c) 18 ≡ 8 (mod 10). Powers of 8 mod 10 also cycle every 4: 8¹≡8, 8²≡4, 8³≡2, 8⁴≡6. 19 ≡ 3 (mod 4) ⇒ 8¹⁹ ≡ 8³ ≡ 2 (mod 10). Multiply the three residues: 6 · 9 · 2 = 108 ≡ 8 (mod 10). Thus, the units digit of P is 8. 4. [Conclusion] The last (units) digit of 16¹⁷ · 17¹⁸ · 18¹⁹ is 8.
